\begin_layout Subsection
Consideration of skewness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a refresher, the following code uses a function `waterfall` discussed
 in the earlier post to calculate gross and net returns for a partnership
 with a 1.5% management and incentive of 20% over an 8% preferred return
 with an 80% catchup.
 We plot the comparative returns and the fee paid to the sponsor as a function
 of gross return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<skew1>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

dmat.df=data.frame(am=1.5,pref=8,catchup=.8,carry=.2) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ret=100+seq(-20,30,.1) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

wat=waterfall(dmat.df,ret) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(wat$grossreturn,wat$grossreturn,col='red',type='l',main='Gross and
 Net Returns', ylab='Return',xlab='Gross Return')
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(wat$grossreturn,wat$netreturn,col='blue') 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

legend('topleft',legend=c('Gross Return','Net Return'),col=c('red','blue'),lwd=1
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculating net returns given a probability distribution assumption for
 gross returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also use the waterfall function to calculate net returns assuming
 a probability distribution of gross returns.
 Suppose we think gross returns are normally distributed, with a mean of
 15% and standard deviation of 15%.
 How are the net returns distributed?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to do this, we are going to create a set of gross returns that
 are distributed according to the above assumption.
 The R language has native capability for this and we simply use the `dnorm`
 function to build the distribution.
 We consider cases plus or minus 3 standard deviations from the mean.
 Note the use of `rep` to replicate more likely values to give them appropriate
 weight in the distribution.
 Then you calculate the returns using the waterfall function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<skew2>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

mu=15 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

sd=15 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ret.seq=seq(mu-3*sd,mu+3*sd,.1) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ret.den=dnorm(ret.seq,mu,sd) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ret.count=round(1000*ret.den) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

ret2=100+rep(ret.seq,ret.count) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

wat2=waterfall(dmat.df,ret2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

with(wat2,plot(density(netreturn),col='blue',main='Return Density',xlab='Gross
 Return')) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

with(wat2,lines(density(grossreturn),col='red')) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

legend('topleft',legend=c('Gross Return','Net Return'),col=c('red','blue'),lwd=1
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we plot a cumulative density function.
 Note the use of `ecdf` to calculate an empirical density on the net returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<skew3>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

with(wat2,plot(ecdf(netreturn),col='blue',pch=20, main='Cumulative Density',xlab
='Gross Return')) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lines(ret.seq,pnorm(ret.seq,mu,sd),col='red',lwd=3) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

legend('topleft',legend=c('Gross Return','Net Return'),col=c('red','blue'),lwd=3
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

@
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we calculate the distribution of fees, i.e.
 the difference between gross and net returns.
 Note the use of `from` in the `density` function to cut off values below
 the minimum fee, which is the asset management fee.
 Contractually, the fees are never lower than that.
 I've added a vertical dotted line at the mean fee.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<skew4>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

fee=wat2$grossreturn-wat2$netreturn 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

mean.fee=mean(fee) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

plot(density(fee,from=min(fee)),col='purple',lwd=2, main='Fee Drag Distribution
\backslash
nGross Return minus Net Return', xlim=c(1,14))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

abline(v=mean.fee,lty='dotted',col='purple') 
\end_layout

